<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="77511" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">Description</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">
Body brownish-black. Head milky yellow (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7531304" captionText="Figure 1. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Habitus, dorsal view; B Habitus, lateral view; C Habitus, ventral view; D Head and thorax, dorsal view; E Face; F Genital capsule, lateral view; G Genital capsule, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604785" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">1</figureCitation>
A and D). Eyes pitch black. Face milky yellow, anteclypeus little darker than fronteclypeus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7531304" captionText="Figure 1. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Habitus, dorsal view; B Habitus, lateral view; C Habitus, ventral view; D Head and thorax, dorsal view; E Face; F Genital capsule, lateral view; G Genital capsule, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604785" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">1</figureCitation>
C and E). Pronotum light yellow with two sides black (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7531304" captionText="Figure 1. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Habitus, dorsal view; B Habitus, lateral view; C Habitus, ventral view; D Head and thorax, dorsal view; E Face; F Genital capsule, lateral view; G Genital capsule, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604785" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">1</figureCitation>
A and D). Scutellum yellowish-brown, with dark basal triangles (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7531304" captionText="Figure 1. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Habitus, dorsal view; B Habitus, lateral view; C Habitus, ventral view; D Head and thorax, dorsal view; E Face; F Genital capsule, lateral view; G Genital capsule, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604785" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">1</figureCitation>
A and D). Forewing brownish (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F7531304" captionText="Figure 1. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Habitus, dorsal view; B Habitus, lateral view; C Habitus, ventral view; D Head and thorax, dorsal view; E Face; F Genital capsule, lateral view; G Genital capsule, ventral view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/604785" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">1</figureCitation>
A and C). Abdominal apodemes broad, extended to 4th sternite (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7531308" captionText="Figure 2. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Pygofer lobe; B Subgenital plate; C Style; D Aedeagus, ventral view; E Abdominal apodemes; F Connective; G Aedeagus, lateral view; H Part of pygofer lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646852" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">2</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="77511" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">Diagnosis</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">Male genitalia</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">
Pygofer lobe broad, with five macroseta at cephalo-ventral angle of lobe and one macroseta at junction area with anal tube (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7531308" captionText="Figure 2. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Pygofer lobe; B Subgenital plate; C Style; D Aedeagus, ventral view; E Abdominal apodemes; F Connective; G Aedeagus, lateral view; H Part of pygofer lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646852" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">2</figureCitation>
A). Pygofer dorsal appendage broad at base, tapering towards apex. Subgenital plate slightly concave near middle area, with two macrosetae on outer surface (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7531308" captionText="Figure 2. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Pygofer lobe; B Subgenital plate; C Style; D Aedeagus, ventral view; E Abdominal apodemes; F Connective; G Aedeagus, lateral view; H Part of pygofer lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646852" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">2</figureCitation>
B). Style with two points at apex; pre-apical lobe small (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7531308" captionText="Figure 2. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Pygofer lobe; B Subgenital plate; C Style; D Aedeagus, ventral view; E Abdominal apodemes; F Connective; G Aedeagus, lateral view; H Part of pygofer lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646852" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">2</figureCitation>
C). Aedeagus with shaft almost straight and flat in lateral view, pair of long processes arising from base of shaft, surpassing gonopore; gonopore reaching 3/4 height of aedeagal shaft, on ventral surface; dorsal apodeme well developed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7531308" captionText="Figure 2. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Pygofer lobe; B Subgenital plate; C Style; D Aedeagus, ventral view; E Abdominal apodemes; F Connective; G Aedeagus, lateral view; H Part of pygofer lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646852" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">2</figureCitation>
D and G). Connective Y-shaped, two lateral arms long and central lobe large; stem well developed (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F7531308" captionText="Figure 2. Anufrievia ventricosa sp. nov. A Pygofer lobe; B Subgenital plate; C Style; D Aedeagus, ventral view; E Abdominal apodemes; F Connective; G Aedeagus, lateral view; H Part of pygofer lobe, dorsal view." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e77511.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/646852" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">2</figureCitation>
F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">Measurement</emphasis>
: Male length (including wing) 2.9 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="77511" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">Etymology</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin word &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">ventricosus</emphasis>
&quot;, referring to the connective central lobe well developed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="77511" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">
This species is similar to 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. confluensa" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511" rank="species" species="confluensa">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="77511">A. confluensa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Tan, Jiang &amp; Song, 2021 with similar shape of style and aedeagus, but can be distinguished by the five macrosetae at cephalo-ventral angle of lobe and one macroseta at junction area with anal tube; the aedeagus with pair of long processes arising from base of shaft and the connective central lobe well developed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
